      "@type": "PropertyValue",
      "name": "description",
      "value": "Systematically test k-point convergence for a representative VASP system (e.g., bulk Si or Al) by scanning k-grid densities (Gamma-centered, Monkhorst-Pack) and monitoring convergence of total energy, forces, stress tensor, and band gap separately. Identify which derived quantities converge at different k-grid densities and under what conditions (metallic vs. semiconducting, cell shape). Produce a diagnostic checklist with quantitative thresholds."
    },
    {
      "@type": "PropertyValue",
      "name": "expected_prediction",
      "value": "Total energy will converge at a coarser k-grid (e.g., 4×4×4 for Si) than forces (6×6×6) and stress tensor (8×8×8). Band gap will converge at an intermediate density (~6×6×6). The gamma-centered grid will converge faster for non-orthorhombic cells. The checklist will identify that a single energy-based convergence threshold (e.g., 1 meV/atom) is insufficient for force- or stress-dependent properties, and that symmetry-reduced k-point counts can mask under-convergence in metals."
    },
